    </ul>
    <h2>Key Considerations for Deciding Between Motor Repair or Replacement</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Cost:</strong> If repair exceeds 65% of replacement, replacement is usually better.</li>
      <li><strong>Motor Design:</strong> For special or obsolete motors, repair may be the only option.</li>
      <li><strong>Age, Size, Lead Time:</strong> Consider the motor’s age, size, repair requirements, and delivery times.</li>
      <li><strong>Performance &amp; Efficiency:</strong> Newer motors may offer better efficiency and reliability.</li>
      <li><strong>Application Review:</strong> Sometimes a better or modified design can improve reliability.</li>
    </ul>
